  <article class="wu cs">
    <p class="cabin-eyebrow">how i work with claude</p>
    <h1 class="wu-title">Measured. Not remembered.</h1>
    <p class="wu-lead">
      Most "how I work with AI" pages are self-description. This one was mined: six months of
      my own working transcripts, extracted blind — one agent per conversation, no priming —
      then an adversarial audit that strips anything the record doesn't support. This is the
      record's description of how I work. Not mine.
    </p>

    <div class="cs-body">
      <section class="md-bubble">
        <h2>It isn't a ladder.</h2>
        <p>
          The clean pipeline — plan, build, verify, ship — is how method pages get written. It
          isn't what the record shows. The real shape is an oscillation: cast wide, narrow on one
          explicit criterion, deliberately widen again. The hard checks sit only at the
          irreversible boundaries — before anything is bought, built on, deleted, deployed, or
          published.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="md-bubble">
        <h2>Eight moves. No order.</h2>
        <p>A palette, not a sequence — reordered, skipped, and re-entered freely. The names are the ones the record uses.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Whiteboard it</strong> — open the idea wide before committing to anything. Scratch pad first, real spec later.</li>
          <li><strong>Cast wide</strong> — survey the full option universe before narrowing. "Scope what's possible, decide later" — scoping and deciding are different acts.</li>
          <li><strong>Fire</strong> — once a fork is clear, pick the lane in one token and go. Deliberation ends abruptly, on purpose.</li>
          <li><strong>Trim to now</strong> — cut to the smallest provable slice; defer the rest to a named later. Ship the proof, then turn the features up.</li>
          <li><strong>Reuse what I own</strong> — hardware, services, and known-good patterns already running are the default substrate. New spend has to justify itself.</li>
          <li><strong>Surgical edit</strong> — "reorder, not revision." Changes are fenced, additive, and leave the working base untouched.</li>
          <li><strong>Lift the mechanism</strong> — a good solve gets pulled out of its instance and made topic-agnostic. Build once; apply across domains.</li>
          <li><strong>Package and hand off</strong> — the terminal act is almost never "publish." It's a durable artifact, or a self-contained prompt handed to the next session.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="md-bubble">
        <h2>Grounded before drafted.</h2>
        <p>
          Nothing gets built on assumed state — the real config, the real output, the real
          measurement goes in first. Execution is a tight paste-the-error loop. Long agent runs
          get babysat: poll, judge stalled, kill, relaunch. Not waited out.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="md-bubble">
        <h2>The method lives in the no.</h2>
        <p>
          The turns are terse, so the criteria are mostly invisible in the affirmative — every
          rejection leaks one. Read off the rejection boundary, the standing kills:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>It contradicts reality I hold firsthand</strong> — the dominant no, by far. Generated output loses to my own measurements, configs, and market prices.</li>
          <li><strong>It asserts claims without evidence</strong> — metrics only when evidenced; a leap gets marked as a leap.</li>
          <li><strong>It edits more than asked</strong> — if no change is needed, don't make one.</li>
          <li><strong>It disrupts what's live</strong> — extend additively; the working thing stays untouched.</li>
          <li><strong>It trades accuracy for speed</strong> — under deadline, scope narrows; the bar doesn't. On legal work the bar is absolute.</li>
          <li><strong>It costs recurring money when owned hardware works</strong> — self-hosted, zero recurring cost, as an architecture filter.</li>
          <li><strong>It flatters instead of leveling</strong> — no sycophancy; if there's a hard truth, face it.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Applied symmetrically: my own prior calls get the same tests, and I ask for the
          counter-case before locking one in.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="md-bubble">
        <h2>What stays a human decision.</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The read</strong> — which mechanism a system actually runs on, and what it's missing.</li>
          <li><strong>The forks</strong> — Claude expands the option surface. Every cut is mine.</li>
          <li><strong>The taste</strong> — what is honest, what is over-claimed, and what ships.</li>
          <li><strong>The flip</strong> — anything public passes a sanitization gate and a review panel, and the keystroke is always mine.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="md-bubble">
        <h2>This site included.</h2>
        <p>
          This page's description of me was mined from the record rather than written from
          memory, adversarially verified, and shipped through the same gates.
        </p>
      </section>
